<subSubSection pageId="48" pageNumber="1151" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="48.[160,1156,718,951]" box="[160,276,718,743]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151">
<heading box="[160,276,718,743]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151" reason="5">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,276,718,743]" inLineHeading="true" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151" reason="3">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="48.[160,1156,718,951]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151">
Recognised by the combination of the following characters: head without a longer erect seta on each side of clypeus, near anteromedial margin of each eye, and between eye and ocellus; pronotum densely covered with setae and punctures, lacking long stout seta on each angle, with callus usually arched, impunctate, shiny; paramere with rounded cone, and usually with denticule, sometimes lacking. Detailed diagnostic characters were provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Pericart J" box="[494,650,927,951]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151" pagination="148 - 154" refId="ref26474" refString="Pericart J. 1967. Note au sujet des caracteres subgeneriques chez les Orius palearctiques (Heteropteres Anthocoridae). Bull Soc Linn Lyon. 36: 148 - 154." type="journal article" year="1967">Péricart (1967</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Pericart J" box="[664,719,927,951]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151" refId="ref26548" refString="Pericart J. 1972. Faune de l ' Europe et du Bassin Mediterraneen. 7. Hemipteres Anthocoridae, Cimicidae et Microphysidae de l ' Ouest-Palearctique. Paris: Masson et C ie Editeurs." type="book" year="1972">1972</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="48" pageNumber="1151" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="48.[160,1156,1017,1215]" box="[160,262,1017,1042]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151">
<heading box="[160,262,1017,1042]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151" reason="5">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,262,1017,1042]" inLineHeading="true" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151" reason="3">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="48.[160,1156,1017,1215]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151">
The subgenus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wagner" authorityYear="1952" box="[333,443,1052,1076]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Orius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Heterorius">
<emphasis box="[333,443,1052,1076]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151">Heterorius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, currently containing 11 species, is widely distributed in the Palearctic Region and in the adjoining areas of the Oriental Region (
<collectingCountry box="[918,1018,1087,1111]" name="Thailand" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151">Thailand</collectingCountry>
) (cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Pericart J" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151" pagination="108 - 140" refId="ref26584" refString="Pericart J. 1996. Family Anthocoridae Fieber, 1836 - flower bugs, minute pirate bugs. In: Aukema B, Rieger CH, editors. Catalogue of the Heteroptera of the Palaearctic Region. Vol. 2. Cimicomorpha I. Amsterdam: The Netherlands Entomological Society; p. 108 - 140." type="book chapter" year="1996">Péricart 1996</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Yasunaga T" box="[231,419,1122,1146]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151" pagination="379 - 386" refId="ref27321" refString="Yasunaga T. 1997 b. The flower bug genus Orius Wolff (Heteroptera, Anthocoridae) from Japan and Taiwan, Part II. Appl Entomol Zool. 32: 379 - 386." type="journal article" year="1997">Yasunaga 1997b</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Aukema B &amp; Rabitsch W &amp; Rieger CH" box="[435,661,1122,1146]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151" refId="ref24521" refString="Aukema B, Rabitsch W, Rieger CH. 2013. Catalogue of the Heteroptera of the Palaearctic Region. Vol. 6. Amsterdam: The Netherlands Entomological Society." type="book" year="2013">Aukema et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). The species with the widest distribution, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Ribaut, 1923)" baseAuthorityName="Ribaut" baseAuthorityYear="1923" box="[160,460,1156,1180]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Orius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vicinus">
<emphasis box="[160,297,1156,1180]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151">Orius vicinus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Ribaut H" box="[310,451,1156,1180]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151" pagination="522 - 538" refId="ref26814" refString="Ribaut H. 1923. Etude sur le genre Triphleps (Heteroptera-Anthocoridae). Bull Soc Hist Nat Toulouse. 51: 522 - 538." type="journal article" year="1923">Ribaut, 1923</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, also occurs in 
<collectingCountry box="[629,777,1156,1180]" name="New Zealand" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
and North America (
<bibRefCitation author="Lariviere MC &amp; Wearing CH" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151" pagination="17 - 21" refId="ref25961" refString="Lariviere MC, Wearing CH. 1994. Orius vicinus (Ribaut) (Heteroptera: Anthocoridae), a predator of orchard pests new to New Zealand. N Z Entomol. 17: 17 - 21." type="journal article" year="1994">Larivière and Wearing 1994</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Lewis TM &amp; Lattin JD" box="[331,582,1191,1215]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1151" pagination="69 - 80" refId="ref26082" refString="Lewis TM, Lattin JD. 2010. Orius (Heterorius) vicinus (Ribaut) (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Anthocoridae) in western North America, a correction of the past. Proc Entomol Soc Wash. 112: 69 - 80." type="journal article" year="2010">Lewis and Lattin 2010</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
